Prologue
"Please!" begged Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She is just a child!" The King of Ice looked at his wife from the top of his throne, his royal advisor standing beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He frowned at this thought.
The little girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue. The King of Ice thought a daughter would make him seem weak. After all, he had only had sons up to that point.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back into the wild. It is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did that.
Frostwell was not always a single kingdom. It had been split into two, the North and the South. In the North, the non-magical kingdom. In the South, a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn themselves apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"Please, my lord, in exchange for my child's life, do with me as you will, imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The King of Ice looked down at his wife, hatred in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he might have mercy on her. The one who had lived with him for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him during his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child may live in the palace," he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself exchanged a horrified glance. She lowered her gaze gently. "Yes, Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered the royal advisor to take the child to one of Eirwen's vacant apartments. Once that was done, he ordered the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the inhabitants of the town could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the townspeople cried out in outrage at seeing their only queen, the kindest among them, about to be killed. Some wept, others screamed and tried to attack the guards, while others wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Release her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made her entrance. The user of fire. The former Queen Eirwen was about to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruellest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the user of fire set the gallows on fire, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the former queen.
"Survive, Kari." This marked the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the furthest room on the left side of the always-frozen southern wing of the palace. The attendants passing by always wondered what was inside that room, afraid of what could be found within. The servants' rumors danced through the corridors. It was believed that the late wife of the King of Ice, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be freed.
"IThey could not be more mistaken," thought Ivory as she walked toward the southern wing, while the attendants passed by whispering among themselves. They do not at all know what is in this room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to her, since she was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?" murmured Ivory at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Iel wondered if she would invite her in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at her shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock came from inside, which seemed to mean that she was there, but after all, where else could she have been?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory, recalling the time when she had entered without asking for permission.
A loud knock echoed from inside. It seemed to mean yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also because of the sound. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room believed to be empty, even though she had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, opening the door slowly. The scene inside the room was unusual, according to the standards of normal people, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered about. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was colder than anywhere else in the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have fallen inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit the space.
"Which notebook are you reading?" asked Ivory as she sat down next to Kari on her bed.
